1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,000
If you ever get a call saying
your computer has a virus —

2
00:00:03,000 --> 00:00:05,500
hang up. Here's what's really going on.

3
00:00:05,500 --> 00:00:09,500
This is a tech support scam —
one of the most common ways

4
00:00:09,500 --> 00:00:12,500
people lose money online.

5
00:00:12,500 --> 00:00:16,000
The truth: Microsoft, Apple, and Google
will NEVER call you

6
00:00:16,000 --> 00:00:19,500
out of the blue to say
your computer has a problem. Never.

7
00:00:19,500 --> 00:00:23,500
What about scary pop-ups?
If a website says

8
00:00:23,500 --> 00:00:27,000
"YOUR COMPUTER IS INFECTED —
CALL THIS NUMBER" — that's fake.

9
00:00:27,000 --> 00:00:30,500
Real virus warnings come from
your antivirus software,

10
00:00:30,500 --> 00:00:33,500
not from a website.

11
00:00:33,500 --> 00:00:37,000
To close a fake pop-up:
press Alt + F4 on Windows,

12
00:00:37,000 --> 00:00:40,000
or Command + Q on a Mac.

13
00:00:40,000 --> 00:00:43,500
Scammers want three things:
remote access to your computer,

14
00:00:43,500 --> 00:00:47,000
your credit card number,
and your personal information.

15
00:00:47,000 --> 00:00:50,500
If you already let someone in:
disconnect from the internet now.

16
00:00:50,500 --> 00:00:54,000
Turn off your WiFi,
then run a full security scan.

17
00:00:54,000 --> 00:00:57,500
Change your passwords from
a different device.

18
00:00:57,500 --> 00:01:01,000
Call your bank if you shared
any payment information.

19
00:01:01,000 --> 00:01:04,500
No real company will ever call you
about a virus.

20
00:01:04,500 --> 00:01:08,000
If someone does — hang up.
Never give them access.

21
00:01:08,000 --> 00:01:10,500
For plain-English guides,
visit TekSure.com.

22
00:01:10,500 --> 00:01:12,000
[END]
